body_text.text:
Imaging studies for patients with SARS complements the clinical diagnosis. Chest radiographs show a ground-glass appearance in the early phase of the infection, which rapidly progresses to focal or diffuse patchy involvement of the lung field (Fig 1
). Unilateral pulmonary consolidation is common in the early phase, although many of them extend bilaterally when the infection becomes more advanced. The radiographic opacities were most evident at 8 to 10 days after the onset of clinical symptoms.13 High-resolution computed tomography may show focal or patchy consolidation before the abnormalities are seen on chest radiographs (Fig 2
).
